cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this work, please cite it as below."
type: software
title: "Data-Efficient and Resource-Aware Fine-Tuning of PubMedBERT for Biomedical Named Entity Recognition: A Comparative Study of Full Fine-Tuning, LoRA, and QLoRA on BC5CDR"
authors:
  - family-names: "Chigurupati"
    given-names: "Venkat Sai Kiran"
version: 1.0.0
date-released: 2025-06-01
license: MIT
repository-code: "https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/pubmedbert-bc5cdr-peft-comparison"
abstract: >
  A controlled, reproducible comparison of Full Fine-Tuning, LoRA, and QLoRA
  for fine-tuning PubMedBERT on the BC5CDR biomedical Named Entity Recognition task.
  The study runs a 24-experiment grid (3 methods × 4 data sizes × 2 seeds) and finds
  that LoRA and QLoRA match or slightly exceed full fine-tuning accuracy while using
  ~20× fewer trainable parameters, 3–4× less GPU memory, and are dramatically more
  data-efficient (9 F1-point lead at 500 training samples).
keywords:
  - biomedical-nlp
  - named-entity-recognition
  - parameter-efficient-fine-tuning
  - lora
  - qlora
  - pubmedbert
  - bc5cdr
  - transformers
  - deep-learning
